The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, July 21 (PTI): The Supreme today refused to stay Karnataka High Courts judgment quashing the order making Kannada the compulsory medium of instruction in all schools from Class I to Class IV.           
	A three-judge bench said if states tried to impose their mother-tongue on students, it could turn counter-productive and make them ineligible even for clerical jobs.                  
	 Lucknow (PTI): The CBI has found that at least six of the 23 missing files of the Ayodhya land deed could have been dumped in the record room marked useless.The agency has found details of these files in a register which keeps a record of files before being dumped, an official said.                   
	 Dehra Dun (PTI): At least nine persons, including five schoolchildren, were killed and 30 injured when their bus fell into a gorge in Dehra Dun district on Tuesday. Four people died on the spot and five on the way to hospital. There were around 60 passengers.                  
	 Washington (PTI): Two US lawmakers have written a letter asking other Congressmen to write to the US defence secretary to allow Sikh youths to serve in the military with their turban. The Congressmen said Captain Kamaljeet S. Kalsi and Captain Tejdeep S. Rattan from New Jersey and New York were not being allowed to wear a turban and an unshorn beard.                  
	 Chennai (PTI): Madras High Court on Tuesday granted anticipatory bail to the medical student and his father whose bail applications had triggered a controversy after a judge alleged that a Union minister had tried to influence him in the case.                   
	 Panaji (PTI): The Goa government has conceded they have been unable to track down a Kenyan and an Ugandan found overstaying. Goa home minister Ravi Naik told the Assembly Julius Musoke from Uganda and Ngoge Mulanda from Kenya were missing since their conviction.                                                                                                                           
